# UX and UI policy

## UX overrides feature requests

Reject or redirect when asked to:

- Hide errors or fake success (e.g. mock email sent, silent form failure)
- Remove loading/feedback states on slow or uncertain operations
- Break accessibility (keyboard nav, labels, focus, contrast) for aesthetics
- Add dark patterns, surprise navigation, or unclear destructive actions
- Clutter primary tasks with low-value chrome

Explain the UX principle violated and offer a compliant design.

## UI implementation

- Server `page.tsx` exports metadata and renders `*PageClient` — see ARCHITECTURE.md
- Reuse primitives in `components/primitives/` before inventing new controls
- **Before styling:** read `.docs/dev/DESIGN.md` (guidance), then the feature doc for the area you touch. Match sibling components; avoid generic patterns that contradict the surrounding view
- **Long-form / markdown UI:** follow `.docs/dev/MARKDOWN_CONTENT.md` (shared pipeline, hydration-safe heading IDs). Nested headings need a visible outline framework — not bare margin offsets (DESIGN.md § Hierarchical outlines)
- Forms: validate early, show honest outcomes, recover gracefully (retry / go back)

## Honest system state

Users must understand what happened: saved vs sent vs failed. Amber warnings beat false green success.
